One reason questions surround <COREF ID="37" TYPE="IDENT">the heat experiments</COREF> is that <COREF ID="37" TYPE="IDENT">they</COREF> involve unusually meticulous measurements .
Typically , the input energy ranges from a third of a watt to one watt and the excess energy is measured in tenths of a watt .
One exception is a continuing experiment at <COREF ID="24" TYPE="IDENT">Stanford University</COREF> where as much as 10 watts of energy are being put into the electrolytic cells .
<COREF ID="2" TYPE="IDENT">A cell filled with heavy water</COREF> is producing 1.0 to 1.5 watts more heat than an identical electrolytic cell filled with ordinary water next to <COREF ID="2" TYPE="IDENT">it</COREF> , reported Turgut M. Gur , an associate of materials scientist Robert A. Huggins , head of the <COREF ID="24" TYPE="IDENT">Stanford</COREF> experimental team .
